node.accessibility_caption: Photo by annvoskamp on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'NO EMPTINESS EVER STAYS EMPTY. EMPTY PLACES always fill. ANN VOSKAMP Vc AV ANNVOSKAMP.COM'.

node.text:
Turns out: Losses leave a wake
that wakes you
to the meaningfulness of what was,
& why it deeply mattered,
& what message you want to live now.

Turns out? It takes uncommon courage to believe:
Losses take
but losses give.
Every loss gives you
space for something else.

Because:
No emptiness ever stays empty.
Empty places always fill.

And we always get to choose what fills the empty places: anger, bitterness, distractions, hardness —
or hope & dreams & love & legacy & more life.

Losses are only wasted if we don't let them give us what they long to give us:

More love, more grace, more gratitude, more wisdom, more Jesus.

It takes uncommon courage to ask:

How might this emptiness be filled with more of what’s fulfilling?
.
.
👉🏼 👉🏼 You, and all you’re bravely facing: What losses are you facing right now — and what are these losses giving you? 
.
#TheBrokenWay #TheWayOfAbundance #1000Gifts

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by annvoskamp on June 20, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'NEVER REALIZED HOW MUCH SAFER THE WORLD FELT BECAUSE MY FATHER WAS IN THE WORLD TOO. ANNVOSKAMP.COM'.

node.text:
It’s a quarter past 11 am on a grey Thursday morning, the very end of April, when my father is killed, & who I once was, or thought I was, dies too.

A child has to learn how to breathe in this world without her father, & I don’t know how to, I’ve never done this before, not even once, & my lungs burn with the gasping.

I never realized, Dad, how much you moved like a sentry along the outer edges of my life, like my own bulwark keeping watch through the night, like a defender of family, like a lookout, always on guard for me.

I never realized how much safer the world felt because my Father was in the world too.

How do you navigate the world when your father’s hands have fallen like the hands of a compass falling?

You were a watchtower always looking out for me when I wasn’t even looking.

You were a shield that I didn’t even know I gripped in a million battles.

You were always the sure voice at the end of the line that felt like a steadying lifeline.

Sometimes you don’t know who you are counting on till they are no longer counted among the living. 

How can there be so many things I forgot and didn’t hold on to, because I magically thought I’d somehow always be holding on to you?

I knew it but I didn’t:

*Listen long while they’re alive, the silence will be so deafening when they’re gone.

Fathers are our fortresses of knowledge, & keepers of the hacks, & masters of the trade called Life.

Fathers are a singular gait you can still see coming across the back lawn like love looking for you, & they are a gate to a million places you can close your eyes & return to anytime you need, & fathers are a remembered line in your mind at just the right time, & you find you’re never lost, you’re never alone, you’re never forsaken.

I am daughter to a father whose eyes misted when he said my name & I am daughter to a father who choked up when he’d close his eyes & say I love you too.

Your father is still with you, always with you.

How is there any other way for a true Father to be, but like the Father: with us.
.
.
From #newpost : I love You, Dad: When You Love Your Father, When You’re Missing Your Father
#linkinbio

node.text:
So I guess it comes down to this when things are hard — in the way they are for all of us — & then when they get kinda even harder, in the way that they do for all of us, what I tell myself in the middle of the night when I’m laying there wide awake: 

Suffering isn’t some unique anomaly, suffering is the universal experience of all humanity. 

Suffering doesn’t mean you’re cursed, suffering means you’re human. 
 
The question isn’t “Why is there brokenness & suffering in my life?” — but “Why wouldn’t there be suffering because such is life in a *broken world?*”
 
Buy the lie that your life is supposed to be heaven on earth, & suffering can be a torturous hell.

But accept & expect that life is a battle, then suffering isn’t a problem, but part of earth’s topography to cross on our way to heaven. 
 
There is no point trying to *question* suffering,
the point is how are you going to *answer* suffering. 
 
The question never is if you understand the *why* of your suffering —
& the answer always is *how* are you going to stand up & walk *through* your suffering. 
 
You don’t have to know the *reason* for your suffering — you only have to know your *response* through the suffering.
 
And this has to be my response to suffering: Surrender. 

Surrender & bravely open your arms cruciform & *welcome* whatever comes. 
 
Our openhanded *welcome*
to *whatever* comes
*invites healing wellness to come.*
 
Surrender to His Story, & welcome the Author Himself & whatever Word He brings.  Wellness comes as we welcome the Word & whatever line He writes into our story. 

God’s promises never claim we won’t be afflicted; He promises we will never be evicted *from God’s presence.*
 
This is always enough.

I wrap this comfort around myself when my aching heart forgets again & again. 
.
.
💛 Check out how we are navigating & the full story on the blog #linkinbio or 👆🏻click through in Stories
.
🔥How are you answering the suffering places in your life — what’s your response and how are you welcoming?🙏💛 (((you)))

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by annvoskamp on May 09, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Parenting is never about how your kids turn out. It's always & only about how you keep turning toward your kids & their Maker. Motherhood is never about training your children to be good so they won't ever fall- it's about letting them see you fall in love every day with a good God. And even after you fallen hard- they see you keep falling hard for God.'.

node.text:
Frankly? You don’t have to know what you’ll do when the kids grow up, buy a Mother’s Day card for you, while they tell their friends, their therapist, & their own kids that you got so much wrong.

You just have to know that you’ll humbly own it.

Because they aren’t wrong.

It’s tender & true: You could have held them longer after they grew too big for your arms: held space for their pain, held their eyes, held them up in relentless prayers.

You could have said yes to more campfires, jumped more on the trampoline & been known more for your loud, rowdy laughter instead of being the ready critic.

You could have asked more honest questions & lingered longer, simply honouring them with listening space.  You could have said yes. And No. Both at the right time.

Where you tried & fell short, they now trip & fall & have bruises to prove it.

Much dysfunction is a function of denying brokenness.

The madness of much dysfunction ends now, ends with our owning it. Yes, things were broken. And: All the brokenness can be the tender breaking open of a seed to grow better.

No matter your hidden regrets or their current age:

You can tenderly own that you took some wrong turns & it’s never too late to simply turn toward the Light.

Life always turns on the turn.

And: Parenting is never about how your kids turn out. It’s always & only about how you keep turning toward your kids and their Maker.

Motherhood is never about training your children to be good so they won’t ever fall — it’s about letting them see you fall in love every day with a good God.

And even after you fallen hard — they see you keep falling hard for God.

Simply: The work of every parent is to give the best they know how now —& the work of every child is to forgive their parents the best they can now.

Our work will look different, but we both have growing work to do.

Come what may this Mother’s Day weekend, there is only always grace & more amazing grace coming to meet us all....
.
And a mother’s labor & delivery never really ends — because it’s the beginning of a love story that works all things out in the end.
.
.
😍(You) Need to disappointment-proof Mother’s Day? Full story on the blog  #linkinbio

node.text:
You may imagine how I’d rather this page in the story was a softer one, less—- jarring: My dear Dad was killed this past week the same way our sister was — both killed under a farm tire in the same farmyard. 

There are stories we find ourselves living that we’d never choose, but this I know in my bones:

God is the Word, & He is more than good, He is kind, & He ultimately only writes good stories. 

This page of the story is not good. And this chapter feels pitch dark & nauseating & we are sorta just staggering through. 

But this page isn’t the end of the story. This chapter isn’t the final chapter.  And the dark doesn’t write the last line. The Word does, the Light does, Love Himself does. 

So: we Stay in His Story,
stay in The Story,
stay & trust that there is only one Word that can re-story & restore all our busted hearts with His. 

...
From Dad’s obituary:

On the farm that he loved, on April 29th, 2021, Bryan Morton, returned to the dust whence he came & which he deeply loved.

Bryan’s love of windmills symbolized his passion for the harnessing of earth & sky, loved the working of the earth, the harvesting of its bounty, & believed farming was his art and poetry. He took his canvas to town & @brussels_four_winds_barn became his magnum opus that he built with his own two hands.

A man of vision, a man of creativity, a man who was never at a loss for an unconventional idea, his unforgettable, worn hands were a testament to an incredible work ethic, a lifetime of ingenuity, and his deep, deep love and service for his family. He was dearly loved & will be dearly missed beyond imagining. 
...

Dad, I promise you,
with everything we’ve been given,
we will live given,
live into a good story
that has cruciform love written into every line... The last line is always a good line, Dad — and you are always loved.

node.text:
... in the middle of lockdown #3 & our 2nd Easter in lockdown, hitting me in tender ways again this weekend in a year of losses: Pain can twist perspective. Grief wears glasses of its own.  Fear can forms cataracts. Heartache can hurts the eyes.

Grief’s tears made Mary Magdalene not recognize Jesus standing right in front of her.

When in reality? Who she was looking for — was looking right at her.

Pain twisted Mary’s perspective into distress over the empty tomb, into thinking they had stole her Lord.

When in reality? Who she thought was taken from her, would now never be taken from her & He would take all of her, forever now.

Fear drove Mary to a dead end place when what she wanted was a life-giving place. Why are you looking for what is life-giving among the dead? Fear. Fear does that. A wrong perspective always drives you in the wrong direction.

Fear always drives you to grave places — when you’re always being called to a place of grace.

And Mary at the empty tomb?

Her perspective, paradigm, point of view, all changed when she heard Him speak her name. 😭😭😭

We see things differently — 
when we’ve heard from Him intimately.

We don’t see things rightly until we’ve heard from Him rightly.

Mary Magdalene testifies:

*Don’t fully trust your eyes — unless you’ve fully trusted His Word.*

You don’t get perspective until you get a Word.

*You can only count on your perspective today —- if you’ve encountered Him today.*

*How you hear — is how you see.*

“Without the lens of the Word — the world warps.” ( #1000Gifts )

But in reality?

Lay your broken heart down on His love letter —- and your eyes break open to see Love everywhere. 🔥💛

Rising always begins when His Word kisses our eyelids — and we open up to love.

All weekend, I keep returning to our ACTUAL REALEST REALITY:

HE IS RISEN & the revolution begins again, where all the hard things are being turned around & undone & turned into good, into amazing grace!

Let all OUR RISINGS BEGIN!
.
.
#RisingPeople 
#StayInTheStory
#LockdownEaster2 #1000Gifts #TheBrokenWay #LiveCruciform

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by annvoskamp on April 04, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Christ rises with His scars because your name is written right into His scars & He can't bear to leave you behind- He means for you to rise too. AA'.

node.text:
So go be like A Woman,
like The Women, & Go & Speak &  Tell everyone you know: 

This is your Lazarus moment.

What was deadening you, is dead.

What was suffocating & strangling you, is finished.

When Christ walked out of that grave, you walked out too.

The rocks have cried out
& your stone has rolled
& Jesus has called your name,
the one that He has written right into His hands,
& you get to rise.

He shows you His scars right now because He doesn’t want you to miss it:

If Christ rises still carrying His scars of suffering —- in Him, scarred, suffering ones can still be the rising ones.

Fold up all you’ve kept shrouded
& walk out.

Lay down your skeletons
& leave.

Take off the old you
& take off.

No shame, no blame, no stain & no grave can now bury anyone who claims His name.

The walking dead
now carry a living hope.

Christ’s conviction on the cross made Him your grave robber & you His witness.

This is no small thing — this is everything! Go & Speak & Tell the world: 

Christ rises with His scars because your name is written right into His scars & He can’t bear to leave you behind —
He means for you to rise too.

Go & rise & tell the world this glory story you have seen!
.
.
👉🏼👉🏼 Swipe to sing the Resurrection Morning song I co-wrote with @ellieholcomb & @sarahmacintosh & is sung with @amygrantofficial, a RISING song from the @faithfulproject who has beautiful RISING THINGS coming our way! GLORY! Like a coming album: Go & Speak! Go & RISE! HE IS ALIVE!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by annvoskamp on April 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Only the Cross SAYS THAT THERE IS A WAY THROUGH, BUT IT WON'T LOOK THE WAY WE'D THOUGHT, BUT IN EVERY ONE OF HIS WAYS HE'S WORKING IN A THOUSAND OTHER WAYS. Trust all of His ways. ANNVOSKAMP.COM'.

node.text:
A burnt & charred Cross hangs over my desk, like all of us have been more than a bit burned this year & everyone’s kinda staggering to the foot of the Cross.

Come with our soot-smeared relationships & the cinders of the story that now won’t ever be.

Come with more than our own stories, come with each other & the injustice of all the parched, come with the collective heartbreak of the fragile & fractured, come with the weight of a whole world of bruised & ruined.

Come to the Cross because there is nowhere else in the world to go with this lament of all cremated hopes.

Because in all the world:

Only the Cross is stretched wide open enough to hold & embrace an ache like ours.

Only the Cross can breathe life across the dying embers of our dreams because He is working in more ways than it seems.

Only the Cross says that what feels like darkness-at-noon moments can be part of destroying all of the dark.

Only the Cross says what looks wrecked can resurrect.

Only the Cross says that there is a Way through, but it won’t look the way we’d thought, but in every one of His ways, He’s working in a thousand other ways.

Trust all of His ways.

And Good Friday says believe in the better mysteries:

Believe death killed death.
And the born can be reborn.
Sin can be consumed by Love,
Debt can be erased by Grace,
And The Nailed One can nail it, kill it & resurrect all of it better than our wildest dreams because His new Kingdom right now is defeating any of evil’s venom.

Good Friday doesn’t just change our own story — Good Friday changes the whole world.

Come to the Cross & the passion of the Christ—
and all our hearts ignite with a love that cannot be razed, our love song to the only One who has ever loved us to death, rising far higher in a glory blaze of its own. 🔥💛
.
.
(Check out the whole story
on the blog #linkinbio or👆link in stories)

node.text:
Maundy Thursday & in the midst of heartbreak & & all kinds of dividing lines, it’s striking: If there’s someone we wouldn’t want at our table, we need to see who Jesus wanted to sit beside at the Last Supper table.

 If Jesus can dip from the same bowl as Judas, we can share the same table, the same space, with anyone, with grace.

Christ prayed that new mandate, that we might be brought to complete unity—& unity doesn’t mean that we paper over our differences.

It means we open the papers of His Word & dialogue—not open fire & destroy.

It means: we stop confusing unity with unanimity. God’s people may not have doctrinal unanimity, but we must have definite unity, if we’re ever to have deep credibility.

It means: Having Christian convictions can’t ever negate having Christ’s compassion. And Christians need to be most careful with words if we are the most Christ—full. 

Is the internet, is the Body of Christ, too scared to break down walls & reach across lines? I’ve been chief among sinner:  Scared that if I reach out to that person–some will conclude that I agree with all of their theology.

What if I was just loving the person?

That’s how the enemy tries to cut the Body with two wires: 

If you disagree with someone on one point—then you must disdain or dismiss them entirely.

And if you acknowledge or affirm someone—then you must agree with them entirely.
*This is a lie. Break it.*

Christ was never scared of guilt by association.
Sure, the watchdogs asked, “Why does he eat with sinners and tax collectors?”

Because He was loving them.  

Obedience to the law of *Love* is the most *expedient way to preach the gospel.*

Love is the the most radically subversive activism of all, the only thing that ever changed any one at all.  

👉🏼 Check out the whole story & what your broken heart, the world, the church needs most. Read full post on the blog, #linkinbio or link in stories 👆🏻

node.text:
No one word has more radically changed my life — or saved me from ending my life — than that one word, and that rarely happens over the whole of a lifetime.
 
True, it was a word that once was all Greek to me, but it became the word that came before all the miracles.
 
And it’s the one word that unfurls Holy Week for me — & not just Holy Week, but all the days & weeks of our lives, making even the hardest things into holy grace. 
 
“And on the night He was BETRAYED… 
Jesus He broke bread & lifted it up & GAVE THANKS.’” 1 Cor 11:23-26
 
“In the original language, “he gave thanks” reads “eucharisteo.”

The root word of eucharisteo is “charis”, meaning grace.

Jesus took the bread & saw it as grace and gave thanks. He took the bread & knew it to be gift & gave thanks.

But there is more: Eucharisteo, thanksgiving, envelopes the Greek word for grace, “charis.” But it also holds its derivative, the Greek word “chara,” meaning joy. Joy!”
~ #1000Gifts
 
Eucharisteo — that one word that has taught me to see grace in all things, so I can give thanks in all things, has shown me the way to joy in all things. 
 
On the night Jesus was betrayed — *He gave thanks.*
 
On the night when the prodigal sliced open your heart, on the night when you lost your job, when your person slammed out the door, and the toilet stopped flushing, & the dog gagged and puked all over the back mat, on the night when it looked like the dawn would never come again — there is always a choice, and why not choose what Jesus did?
 
Because when Jesus had to fight through dark, staring right into the most impossible situation of the Cross — what does He do? 
 
Out of a universe of supernatural options at the tip of His fingers — what does Jesus do? 

On the night when Jesus was betrayed — *He gave thanks.*

If Jesus can give thanks in that — *we can give thanks in everything.*

//

Read the rest of this post, experience our new updated site (!!!), see how you can grab your own FREE Joy Tool Kit, & check out the latest book that’s all gussied up for her 10th! —> http://bit.ly/Eucharisteo
#newpost #linkinbio

📷2&9: @joyprouty

node.text:
... so, yeah, honestly? This past year, more than any other, has led me to realize:

Jesus is not a belief to me,
He is breath to me,
not some theory, but all my gravity,
not a lens for my life, but He is my life.

The Triune God is not one sphere of some multi-dimensional life —
He is atmosphere, terra, lung & the only way to not suffocate in self.

It’s true: people may almost universally believe that Jesus is a good person, but the only way to have a good life is to choose Jesus as your whole universe. 

And we aren’t good news, evangelical Christians, if we believe the fake news that Christianity is only the mental assent of faith in Jesus, without requiring the lived allegiance of faithfulness to Jesus.

The Gospel truth is that believing in Jesus is being saved by a faith that is committed to a life of faithfulness.

It’s the covenantal faithfulness of Christ alone that saves us, & we respond to His saving faithfulness, by covenanting our own faithfulness to Him.

(And just because we will be faithless 😭, doesn’t mean that it’s less important that we commit to reorienting ourselves back toward faithfulness again & again). 

For too long, maybe we’ve lived a cheap faith, instead of a costly faithfulness.

So, I’m turning & I’m daring to believe it & desperately trying to live it:

Following Jesus will cost you laying down the kingdom of self to give you *the upside down kingdom that has only upsides for all eternity.*

Only in the Real Universe of the Upside Down Kingdom, does Real Hope exist, where death has been killed at the Cross, where life has meaning beyond the walls of this earth,  where Hope has a name & rose from the grave & engraved your name on the palms of His hands. 

In these strange days:
There is more than believing in God.
There is flat out enjoying living in God 🙏🔥💛
.
.
👉🏼 Catch my whole heart tonight @ifgathering (free for anyone to tune in & share the  h o p e 💛🙏)
